{"id":"cond-mat/0603499","submitter":"Fabien Alet","authors":"Fabien Alet, Gregoire Misguich, Vincent Pasquier, Roderich Moessner\n  and Jesper Lykke Jacobsen","title":"Unconventional continuous phase transition in a three dimensional dimer\n  model","comments":"4 pages, 3 figures; v2: minor changes, published version","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 97, 030403 (2006)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.97.030403","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech","license":null,"abstract":"  Phase transitions occupy a central role in physics, due both to their\nexperimental ubiquity and their fundamental conceptual importance. The\nexplanation of universality at phase transitions was the great success of the\ntheory formulated by Ginzburg and Landau, and extended through the\nrenormalization group by Wilson. However, recent theoretical suggestions have\nchallenged this point of view in certain situations. In this Letter we report\nthe first large-scale simulations of a three-dimensional model proposed to be a\ncandidate for requiring a description beyond the Landau-Ginzburg-Wilson\nframework: we study the phase transition from the dimer crystal to the Coulomb\nphase in the cubic dimer model. Our numerical results strongly indicate that\nthe transition is continuous and are compatible with a tricritical universality\nclass, at variance with previous proposals.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Mar 2006 09:09:45 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 24 Jul 2006 10:03:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-11"}
{"id":"cond-mat/0603500","submitter":"Mauro Sbragaglia Dr","authors":"M. Sbragaglia and K. Sugiyama","title":"Boundary induced non linearities at small Reynolds Numbers","comments":"29 pages, 10 figures","journal-ref":"Physica D 228, 140-147 (2007)","doi":"10.1016/j.physd.2007.03.004","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.other nlin.CG physics.flu-dyn","license":null,"abstract":"  We investigate the influence of boundary slip velocity in Newtonian fluids at\nfinite Reynolds numbers. Numerical simulations with Lattice Boltzmann method\n(LBM) and Finite Differences method (FDM) are performed to quantify the effect\nof heterogeneous boundary conditions on the integral and local properties of\nthe flow. Non linear effects are induced by the non homogeneity of the boundary\ncondition and change the symmetry properties of the flow inducing an overall\nmean flow reduction. To explain the observed drag modification, reciprocal\nrelations for stationary ensembles are used, predicting a reduction of the mean\nflow rate from the creeping flow to be proportional to the fourth power of the\nfriction Reynolds number. Both numerical schemes are then validated within the\ntheoretical predictions and reveal a pronounced numerical efficiency of the LBM\nwith respect to FDM.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 20 Mar 2006 09:40:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-11"}
